      <body>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p/>
         </div>
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" ref="#person95"><name nymRef="Ἰουλιανός"><supplied reason="lost">Ἰ</supplied>ουλαν<unclear>οῦ</unclear></name>
                  <persName type="attested" ref="#person96"><name nymRef="Ἄρειος">Ἀρήου</name></persName></persName>.
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">И</supplied>улиана, сына Ария.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Of Julian, son of Areios.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" xml:lang="ru">
            <p> Латышев (1918b, 17, № 10, рис. 1) оставил надпись без прочтения.</p>
                <p> Пропуск йоты в имени Иулиан — видимо, случайность. Если наше чтение верно, то мы имеем одну из немногих надписей с патронимиком из 
                   Херсона  (ср. <ref type="inscription">V 83</ref><!--byz083-->.2, <ref type="inscription">V 85</ref><!--byz085-->, 
                   <ref type="inscription">V 267</ref><!--byz255-->, <ref type="inscription">V 283</ref><!--byz271-->, <ref type="inscription">V 286</ref><!--byz274-->). 
                   Оба имени — христианские (см. Delehaye 1902, 41 etc., 732).</p>
                <p> Археологический контекст находки неизвестен. </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Latyshev (1918b, 17, № 10, fig. 1) did not offer a reading of this text.</p>
            <p>A missing iota in the name Julian is probably unintentional. If our reading is correct, then we have one of only a few examples of the use of a patronymic
               in an inscription from Cherson  (cf. <ref type="inscription">V 83</ref><!--byz083-->.2, <ref type="inscription">V 85</ref><!--byz085-->, 
               <ref type="inscription">V 267</ref><!--byz255-->, <ref type="inscription">V 283</ref><!--byz271-->, <ref type="inscription">V 286</ref><!--byz274-->). 
               Both names are Christian.</p>
            <p>The archaeological context of this find is unknown.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
